        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-10-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-10-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="111"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                <head>111. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_HR1" type="from">Robert
                        Hormats</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="to"
                        >Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d111fn1">Source:
                        National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential
                        Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 542, Country
                        Files, Far East, Korea, Vol. IV, 1 Jan–31 Dec 1971. No classification
                        marking. Sent for information. Concurred in by <persName corresp="#p_HJH1"
                            >Holdridge</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-10-05">October 5, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Joint Communiqué from <persName corresp="#p_SMH1">Stans</persName>’
                        Meeting with the Korean Security of Commerce</item>
                </list>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SMH1">Stans</persName> has sent you a copy of the
                    joint communiqué (Tab A)<note n="2" xml:id="d111fn2">Attached but not printed.
                            <persName corresp="#p_SMH1">Stans</persName> sent <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> the joint communiqué under a
                        September 29 covering memorandum. (Ibid.)</note> from his meeting with Nak
                    Sun Lee, Korea’s Minister of Commerce and Industry. The meetings took place in
                    Washington on September 27–28.</p>
                <p>The salient points are: <list>
                        <item>—<persName corresp="#p_SMH1">Stans</persName> emphasized the
                            objectives of the President’s new economic policy and <persName
                                corresp="#p_LHR1">Lee</persName> reviewed the impressive development
                            achievements under Korea’s last development plan and outlined goals
                            envisaged in its next plan.</item>
                        <item>—<persName corresp="#p_LHR1">Lee</persName> noted that the U.S. ten
                            percent surcharge on imports might adversely affect Korea’s exports to
                            the U.S. and urged that it be <pb facs="0313" n="286" xml:id="pg_286"/>
                            removed as soon as possible. <persName corresp="#p_SMH1"
                                >Stans</persName> reaffirmed that the surcharge was a temporary
                            measure.</item>
                        <item>—<persName corresp="#p_LHR1">Lee</persName> emphasized the desire of
                            Korea to encourage more U.S. equity investment, particularly in joint
                            ventures with Korean partners. <persName corresp="#p_SMH1"
                                >Stans</persName> indicated that U.S. firms will continue to be
                            interested in Korea as long as the investment climate remains
                            favorable.</item>
                        <item>—<persName corresp="#p_LHR1">Lee</persName> requested increased
                            support for U.S. exports to Korea by the <gloss target="#t_Ex1"
                                >Ex-Im</gloss> Bank. <persName corresp="#p_SMH1">Stans</persName>
                            took note of the request.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The discussions were frank and cordial. <persName corresp="#p_SMH1"
                        >Stans</persName> will go to Seoul to meet with <persName corresp="#p_LHR1"
                        >Lee</persName> next year.</p>
            </div>
